05868nam a22009015i 9780674275744DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742757447 a10.4159/97806742757442doi  a(DE-B1597)627106  a(OCoLC)1323254768  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aLIT0042102bisacsh04a305.892/4047223//eng/20220616eng  aNY 4780qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/132360:1 aSenderovich, Sasha, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHow the Soviet Jew Was Made /cSasha Senderovich. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on Transliteration and Translation -- tMaps -- tIntroduction: Dispersion of the Pale -- t1 Haunted by Pogroms -- t2 Salvaged Fragments -- t3 The Edge of the World -- t4 Back in the USSR -- t5 The Soviet Jew as a Trickster -- tEpilogue: Returns to the Shtetl -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNational Jewish Book Awards FinalistA close reading of postrevolutionary Russian and Yiddish literature and film recasts the Soviet Jew as a novel cultural figure: not just a minority but an ambivalent character navigating between the Jewish past and Bolshevik modernity.The Russian Revolution of 1917 transformed the Jewish community of the former tsarist empire. The Pale of Settlement on the empire's western borderlands, where Jews had been required to live, was abolished several months before the Bolsheviks came to power. Many Jews quickly exited the shtetls, seeking prospects elsewhere. Some left for bigger cities, others for Europe, America, or Palestine. Thousands tried their luck in the newly established Jewish Autonomous Region in the Far East, where urban merchants would become tillers of the soil. For these Jews, Soviet modernity meant freedom, the possibility of the new, and the pressure to discard old ways of life.This ambivalence was embodied in the Soviet Jew—not just a descriptive demographic term but a novel cultural figure. In insightful readings of Yiddish and Russian literature, films, and reportage, Sasha Senderovich finds characters traversing space and history and carrying with them the dislodged practices and archetypes of a lost Jewish world. There is the Siberian settler of Viktor Fink’s Jews in the Taiga, the folkloric trickster of Isaac Babel, and the fragmented, bickering family of Moyshe Kulbak’s The Zelmenyaners, whose insular lives are disrupted by the march of technological, political, and social change. There is the collector of ethnographic tidbits, the pogrom survivor, the émigré who repatriates to the USSR.Senderovich urges us to see the Soviet Jew anew, as not only a minority but also a particular kind of liminal being. How the Soviet Jew Was Made emerges as a profound meditation on culture and identity in a shifting landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aJews in literature. 0aJews in motion pictures. 0aJews in popular culturezSoviet Union. 0aJewszSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aRussian literaturexJewish authorsy20th century. 0aWandering Jew in literature. 0aYiddish literaturezSoviet Union. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh  aBirobidzhan.  aBolshevik Revolution.  aCinema.  aDavid Bergelson.  aDovid Bergelson.  aIsaac Babel.  aJewish Culture.  aJews in the Soviet Union.  aLiterature.  aMoyshe Kulbak.  aPogroms.  aRussian Jewish.  aShtetl.  aSoviet Jewry.  aSoviet Yiddish.  aSoviet.  aStalin.  aWandering Jew.  aYiddish.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908